# {{.AppName}} (eletrocromo Android)

Generated ad-hoc Android host for package **`{{.PackageID}}`**.

Same model as desktop: Go owns loopback HTTP + auth; this project is a dumb
WebView shell + foreground service that runs the packaged binary.

## Layout

| Path | Role |
|------|------|
| `eletrocromo.json` | Generator config (re-run / rebuild inputs) |
| `app/` | Kotlin WebView + ServerService |
| `app/src/main/jniLibs/<abi>/libeletrocromo.so` | Cross-compiled Go app (`ELETROCROMO_NO_UI=1`) |
| `scripts/build-go.sh` | Multiarch `go build` into jniLibs |

## Prerequisites

- JDK 17+
- Android SDK (platform 35) + build-tools; `ANDROID_HOME` set
- Go toolchain that can `GOOS=android` with `CGO_ENABLED=0`
- Gradle 8.9+ (or open in Android Studio to bootstrap the wrapper)

## Build Go binary (multiarch)

From this directory (after pointing `go_main` in `eletrocromo.json`):

```bash
./scripts/build-go.sh
```

ABIs: `arm64-v8a`, `armeabi-v7a`, `x86_64`.

Your Go `main` should call `eletrocromo.App.Run()` with
`ID: "{{.PackageID}}"`. The service sets `ELETROCROMO_NO_UI=1` so Helium is
skipped and a parseable `ELETROCROMO_READY <url>` line is logged.

## Assemble APK

```bash
# if no gradlew yet:
gradle wrapper
./gradlew assembleDebug
# APK: app/build/outputs/apk/debug/app-debug.apk
```

## Regenerate

From the eletrocromo repo:

```bash
go run ./cmd/eletrocromo android create \
  --id {{.PackageID}} \
  --name {{.AppName | printf "%q"}} \
  --out <this-dir> \
  --force
```

Do not hand-edit generated Kotlin if you expect to re-run `create --force`;
put app logic in the Go module instead.
